Vheadline
p2
VFive days of musical bliss
p3
sVnews
p4
VGayaka Sarvabhowma Sangeeta Parishat and Swarajhari, Vijayawada, jointly celebrated the 126th Jayanthi of Parupalli Ramakrishnaiah Pantulu, a renowned musician and guru, for five days at Sri Sivaramakrishna Kshetram. This year the organisation honoured Manda Sudharani of Visakhapatnam with the title &#8216;Sunada Sudha Nidhi&#8217;.The meeting was followed by an excellent vocal concert by Sudharani, a specialist in rendering rare and intricate pallavis. The organisation also dedicated each day&#8217;s programme to a vidwan of yesteryear and contemporaries of Parupalli Ramakrishnaiah Pantulu. Sudharani started her concert withBagayenayyain Chandra Jyothi.Nanu Palimpain Mohana was efficiently rendered by her with aesthetically satisfying raga delineation and crisp kalpana swaras. The highlight of Sudharani&#8217;s concert was the fine pallaviApoorva Kalyani &#8212; Apara Karunantaranginin Poorvikalyani set to Misra Chapu talam. The pallavi was adorned with melodious alapana and the swaras were efficient and mathematically precise. The engaging concert came to a close with a thillana in Revathi. Sudharani had fine support from B.V. Durga Bhavani on violin and K. Sadgurucharan on the mridangam. First day&#8217;s programme was dedicated to mridanga vidwan Aswadhati Ramamurthy.Reputed vocalist Manda Krishna Mohan presented a vocal concert on the second day.  Starting withKalyani Ata Tala Varnamhe went on to singSri Ganesatparamin a rare ragaVeena VadiniandAnnapoorne VisalakshiinSama. Sumptuoustodiwas presented as his main itemKoluvamare gada Kodandapaniin which Krishna Mohan exhibited hismanodharmamability well. Another attractive item in his concert was his rendering of theAshtapadiRadhika Krishna. He was well supported on violin and mridangam by P. Nageswara Rao and P.S. Phalgun respectively. The programme was dedicated to the legendary Harikatha exponent Adibhatla Narayana Das.Patibandla Janaki of Guntur sang on the third day. An experienced singer with goodpathantaram, Janaki began with avarnamin Hindola composed by her guru Annavarapu Ramaswamy and followed withDharma Samvardhaniin Madhyamavathi andKaruna joodiin Sri ragam. The main itemNinne Namminanuin Simhendra Madhyamam was rendered with fine alapana and kalpana swaras.Good instrumental support came from P. Nanda Kumar (violin) and M.L.N. Raju (mridangam). The programme was dedicated to Hari Nagabhushanam, a great vidwan of Machilipatnam.There was a rare programme on the fourth day.NaukaCharitram, one of the three musical plays written by Thyagaraja was impressively presented by C.V.P. Sastri, D. Ravikant, M. Anjana Sudhakar, R. Sarvani, M. Nagalakshmi and D. Prameela. The rendering was finely co-ordinated and neatly presented by the group with instrumental support  from P. Nageswara Rao (violin), K. Sasidhar (veena), K. Sai Giridhar (mridangam) and R. Prem Kumar (flute).  This day&#8217;s programme was dedicated to the Veena Maestro Tumarada Sangameswara Sastri of Pithapuram.The five day musical treat came to a close with a melodious violin duet by B.V. Durga Bhavani and P. Nandakumar. They started crisply with the Pancharatna keertanaSadhinchenin Arabhi and kept up the fine tempo till the end. Other keertanas they played wereManaviyalakimparadatein Nalinakanthi,Garuda Gamanain Nagaswaravali,Mamava Madhavaa tarangam in Neelambari and a thillana in Pharaj.The main itemNagumomuGanaleniin Abheri waspresented by Bhavani and Nandakumar. M.L.N. Raju and M. Haribabu gave them fine support on mridangam and ghatam respectively. The last day&#8217;s programme was dedicated to the legendary violin maestro Dwaram Venkataswamy Naidu of Vizianagaram.
